{"format":"tiptap/v1","updatedAt":"2026-06-21T17:36:26.557Z","doc":{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Jacobian and Hessian matrices"},{"type":"text","text":" are higher-order derivatives that generalize the gradient and derivative concepts to handle functions with multiple inputs and outputs. The Jacobian captures "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"first-order sensitivity"},{"type":"text","text":" (how each output changes with each input), while the Hessian captures "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"second-order curvature"},{"type":"text","text":" (how the rate of change itself changes), enabling advanced optimization and deeper understanding of model behavior."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What it is — Clear definition and intuition"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Gradient (1st-order, scalar output):"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For a function "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"f(x₁, x₂,..., xₙ)"},{"type":"text","text":" that outputs a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"single number"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"∇f = [∂f/∂x₁, ∂f/∂x₂, ..., ∂f/∂xₙ]  (vector, n×1)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Gradient = vector of partial derivatives"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Jacobian (1st-order, vector output):"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For a function "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"g(x₁, x₂,..., xₙ)"},{"type":"text","text":" that outputs "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"multiple numbers"},{"type":"text","text":" (g₁, g₂,..., gₘ):"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"J_g = [∂g₁/∂x₁  ∂g₁/∂x₂  ...  ∂g₁/∂xₙ]\n      [∂g₂/∂x₁  ∂g₂/∂x₂  ...  ∂g₂/∂xₙ]\n      [  ...      ...    ...    ...   ]\n      [∂gₘ/∂x₁  ∂gₘ/∂x₂  ...  ∂gₘ/∂xₙ]  (matrix, m×n)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Jacobian = matrix of ALL partial derivatives"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian (2nd-order, scalar output):"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For a function "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"f(x₁, x₂,..., xₙ)"},{"type":"text","text":" that outputs a single number:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"H_f = [∂²f/∂x₁²   ∂²f/∂x₁∂x₂  ...  ∂²f/∂x₁∂xₙ]\n      [∂²f/∂x₂∂x₁ ∂²f/∂x₂²    ...  ∂²f/∂x₂∂xₙ]\n      [  ...        ...       ...    ...      ]\n      [∂²f/∂xₙ∂x₁ ∂²f/∂xₙ∂x₂  ...  ∂²f/∂xₙ²  ]  (matrix, n×n)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Hessian = matrix of ALL second-order partial derivatives"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Quick comparison:"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Concept"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Output type"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Structure"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Size"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Meaning"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Gradient"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Scalar (1 number)"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Vector"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n×1"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Direction of steepest ascent"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Jacobian"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Vector (m numbers)"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Matrix"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"m×n"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sensitivity of all outputs to all inputs"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Hessian"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Scalar (1 number)"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Matrix"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n×n"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Curvature of the function"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Key insight"},{"type":"text","text":": Jacobian generalizes gradient to vector-valued functions; Hessian generalizes derivative to second-order"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Why it matters — Importance in Generative AI"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Jacobian and Hessian matrices enable advanced ML techniques beyond basic gradient descent:"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ML Application"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"How Jacobian/Hessian applies"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sensitivity Analysis"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Jacobian shows how sensitive each output is to each input"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Parameter Tuning"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Jacobian guides tuning models with vector-valued outputs"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Newton's Method"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian enables second-order optimization (faster convergence)"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Curvature Analysis"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian tells if landscape is steep/flat, convex/concave"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Local Minima Detection"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Positive definite Hessian = local minimum"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Model Interpretability"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Jacobian reveals which inputs affect which outputs"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Optimization"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian eigenvalues indicate \"ravines\" causing slow convergence"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Regularization"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian-based methods improve generalization"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Real example"},{"type":"text","text":": In training a neural network with 10 output classes, the Jacobian tells you how changing weight w₁ affects output class 1, class 2,..., class 10 separately."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Benefits — Key advantages"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Multi-output handling"},{"type":"text","text":": Jacobian handles functions with many outputs"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sensitivity mapping"},{"type":"text","text":": Jacobian shows input-output relationships"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Curvature information"},{"type":"text","text":": Hessian reveals landscape shape"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Faster convergence"},{"type":"text","text":": Newton's method with Hessian converges faster than gradient descent"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Optimal point detection"},{"type":"text","text":": Hessian eigenvalues classify minima/maxima"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Model interpretability"},{"type":"text","text":": Jacobian reveals which features drive outputs"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Trade-offs — Downsides and limitations"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Trade-off"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Impact"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Computational cost"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Jacobian: O(mn) computations; Hessian: O(n²) second derivatives"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Memory usage"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian for million-parameter model = 10¹² elements (petabytes)"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Numerical instability"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian inversion can be unstable (ill-conditioned)"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Complexity"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Harder to implement and debug than gradients"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Rarely used"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Most ML uses only gradients; Hessians are expensive"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"How it works — Step-by-step computation"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Computing Jacobian:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Example"},{"type":"text","text":": Function "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"g(x, y)"},{"type":"text","text":" outputs 2 numbers:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# g₁(x, y) = x² + y\n# g₂(x, y) = xy + y³\n\n# Partial derivatives:\n∂g₁/∂x = 2x\n∂g₁/∂y = 1\n∂g₂/∂x = y\n∂g₂/∂y = x + 3y²\n\n# Jacobian matrix (2×2):\nJ = [∂g₁/∂x  ∂g₁/∂y]   = [2x    1]\n    [∂g₂/∂x  ∂g₂/∂y]     [y  x + 3y²]\n\n# Evaluate at point (1, 2):\nJ(1, 2) = [2×1    1]   = [2  1]\n          [2  1 + 3×4]   [2 13]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Python (NumPy)"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import numpy as np\n\ndef g(x, y):\n    g1 = x**2 + y\n    g2 = x*y + y**3\n    return np.array([g1, g2])\n\n# Compute Jacobian at (1, 2)\nx, y = 1.0, 2.0\nh = 1e-5\n\n# Partial derivatives numerically\ndg1_dx = (g(x+h, y)[0] - g(x, y)[0]) / h\ndg1_dy = (g(x, y+h)[0] - g(x, y)[0]) / h\ndg2_dx = (g(x+h, y) [linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/how-jacobian-hessian-matrices-used-machine-learning-ajit-jaokar-th7kf) - g(x, y) [linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/how-jacobian-hessian-matrices-used-machine-learning-ajit-jaokar-th7kf)) / h\ndg2_dy = (g(x, y+h) [linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/how-jacobian-hessian-matrices-used-machine-learning-ajit-jaokar-th7kf) - g(x, y) [linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/how-jacobian-hessian-matrices-used-machine-learning-ajit-jaokar-th7kf)) / h\n\nJ = np.array([[dg1_dx, dg1_dy],\n              [dg2_dx, dg2_dy]])\n\nprint(f\"Jacobian: {J}\")  # [[2, 1], [2, 13]]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Python (PyTorch)"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import torch\n\nx = torch.tensor([1.0, 2.0], requires_grad=True)\n\ndef g(xyz):\n    x, y = xyz[0], xyz [linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/how-jacobian-hessian-matrices-used-machine-learning-ajit-jaokar-th7kf)\n    return torch.stack([x**2 + y, x*y + y**3])\n\ny = g(x)\n\n# Compute Jacobian\nJ = torch.zeros(2, 2)\nfor i in range(2):\n    y[i].backward(retain_graph=True)\n    J[i] = x.grad\n    x.grad.zero_()\n\nprint(f\"Jacobian: {J}\")  # [[2, 1], [2, 13]]"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Computing Hessian:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Example"},{"type":"text","text":": Function "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"f(x, y)"},{"type":"text","text":" outputs 1 number:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# f(x, y) = x² + xy + y³\n\n# First derivatives (gradient):\n∂f/∂x = 2x + y\n∂f/∂y = x + 3y²\n\n# Second derivatives (Hessian):\n∂²f/∂x² = 2          (derivative of 2x + y w.r.t. x)\n∂²f/∂x∂y = 1         (derivative of 2x + y w.r.t. y)\n∂²f/∂y∂x = 1         (derivative of x + 3y² w.r.t. x)\n∂²f/∂y² = 6y         (derivative of x + 3y² w.r.t. y)\n\n# Hessian matrix (2×2):\nH = [∂²f/∂x²   ∂²f/∂x∂y]  = [2   1]\n    [∂²f/∂y∂x  ∂²f/∂y²]    [1  6y]\n\n# Evaluate at point (1, 2):\nH(1, 2) = [2   1]\n          [1  12]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Python (SymPy)"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import sympy as sp\n\nx, y = sp.symbols('x y')\nf = x**2 + x*y + y**3\n\n# Gradient\ngradient = [sp.diff(f, x), sp.diff(f, y)]\n# [2*x + y, x + 3*y**2]\n\n# Hessian\nH = sp.hessian(f, [x, y])\n# [[2, 1],\n#  [1, 6*y]]\n\n# Evaluate at (1, 2)\nH_at_point = H.subs({x: 1, y: 2})\n# [[2, 1],\n#  [1, 12]]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Python (NumPy numerical)"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import numpy as np\n\ndef f(x, y):\n    return x**2 + x*y + y**3\n\n# Compute Hessian at (1, 2)\nx, y = 1.0, 2.0\nh = 1e-4\n\n# Second derivatives numerically\ndf_dx = (f(x+h, y) - f(x-h, y)) / (2*h)\ndf_dy = (f(x, y+h) - f(x, y-h)) / (2*h)\n\nd2f_dx2 = (f(x+h, y) - 2*f(x, y) + f(x-h, y)) / h**2\nd2f_dy2 = (f(x, y+h) - 2*f(x, y) + f(x, y-h)) / h**2\nd2f_dxdy = (f(x+h, y+h) - f(x+h, y-h) - f(x-h, y+h) + f(x-h, y-h)) / (4*h**2)\n\nH = np.array([[d2f_dx2, d2f_dxdy],\n              [d2f_dxdy, d2f_dy2]])\n\nprint(f\"Hessian: {H}\")  # [[2, 1], [1, 12]]"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Key properties — Mathematical rules"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Jacobian properties:"}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Chain rule"},{"type":"text","text":": For "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"f(g(x))"},{"type":"text","text":", Jacobian is:"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"``"},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":" J_{f∘g} = J_f · J_g (matrix multiplication) "},{"type":"text","text":"``"}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Generalizes gradient"},{"type":"text","text":": For scalar output (m=1), Jacobian = gradient transpose"}]}]}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Coordinate transforms"},{"type":"text","text":": Used in changing variables (e.g., polar → Cartesian)"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian properties:"}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Symmetric"},{"type":"text","text":": Hᵢⱼ = Hⱼᵢ (mixed partials equal)"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"``"},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":" ∂²f/∂x∂y = ∂²f/∂y∂x "},{"type":"text","text":"``"}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Eigenvalues indicate curvature"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"All positive"},{"type":"text","text":" → local minimum (convex) - "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"All negative"},{"type":"text","text":" → local maximum (concave) - "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Mixed signs"},{"type":"text","text":" → saddle point"}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Positive definite"},{"type":"text","text":" → local minimum"}]}]}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Newton's method"},{"type":"text","text":": Uses Hessian for second-order update:"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"``"},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":" w ← w - H⁻¹∇L(w) (faster than gradient descent) "},{"type":"text","text":"``"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"When to use it — Scenarios and decision criteria"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use Jacobian when:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Vector-valued function"},{"type":"text","text":": Model has multiple outputs (e.g., 10-class classification)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sensitivity analysis"},{"type":"text","text":": Need to know how each output responds to each input"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Backpropagation"},{"type":"text","text":": Computing gradients through neural network layers"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Coordinate transforms"},{"type":"text","text":": Changing variable systems"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use Hessian when:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Second-order optimization"},{"type":"text","text":": Need faster convergence (Newton's method)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Curvature analysis"},{"type":"text","text":": Understand landscape shape (steep/flat, convex/concave)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Local minima detection"},{"type":"text","text":": Classify optimal points"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Ill-conditioned problems"},{"type":"text","text":": Diagnose \"ravines\" causing zigzagging"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use gradient when:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"❌ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Standard optimization"},{"type":"text","text":": Most ML uses first-order gradients only (simpler, faster)"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"How to implement — Practical examples"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Example 1: Neural network Jacobian"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\n# Neural network with 3 inputs, 5 outputs\nmodel = nn.Sequential(\n    nn.Linear(3, 10),\n    nn.ReLU(),\n    nn.Linear(10, 5)\n)\n\n# Input\nx = torch.randn(1, 3, requires_grad=True)\n\n# Compute Jacobian of output w.r.t. input\noutput = model(x)\n\nJ = torch.zeros(5, 3)\nfor i in range(5):\n    output[i].backward(retain_graph=True)\n    J[i] = x.grad\n    x.grad.zero_()\n\nprint(f\"Jacobian shape: {J.shape}\")  # (5, 3)\n# Each row i shows how output[i] changes with each input"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Example 2: Newton's method with Hessian"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import numpy as np\n\n# Function: f(x) = x²\ndef f(x):\n    return x**2\n\n# Gradient: f'(x) = 2x\ndef gradient(x):\n    return 2*x\n\n# Hessian: f''(x) = 2\ndef hessian(x):\n    return 2\n\n# Newton's method (2nd-order optimization)\nx = 5.0\nfor i in range(5):\n    grad = gradient(x)\n    Hess = hessian(x)\n    \n    # Update: w ← w - H⁻¹∇L\n    x = x - grad / Hess\n    \n    print(f\"Iteration {i}: x = {x:.6f}, f(x) = {f(x):.6f}\")\n\nprint(f\"Final: x = {x:.6f}, f(x) = {f(x):.6f}\")  # x ≈ 0, f(x) ≈ 0"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Why faster than gradient descent?"},{"type":"text","text":"\n- Gradient descent: "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"x = x - η × 2x"},{"type":"text","text":" (depends on learning rate η)\n- Newton: "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"x = x - 2x/2 = 0"},{"type":"text","text":" (one step to optimum!)"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Example 3: Hessian for minima detection"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import numpy as np\n\n# Function: f(x, y) = x² + y² (bowl shape)\ndef f(x, y):\n    return x**2 + y**2\n\n# Hessian at (0, 0)\nH = np.array([[2, 0],\n              [0, 2]])\n\n# Eigenvalues\neigenvalues = np.linalg.eigvals(H)\nprint(f\"Eigenvalues: {eigenvalues}\")  # [2, 2]\n\n# Both positive → local minimum ✓\nif np.all(eigenvalues > 0):\n    print(\"Point is a local MINIMUM\")"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Compare with saddle point"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Function: f(x, y) = x² - y² (saddle)\nH_saddle = np.array([[2, 0],\n                     [0, -2]])\n\neigenvalues_saddle = np.linalg.eigvals(H_saddle)\nprint(f\"Eigenvalues: {eigenvalues_saddle}\")  # [2, -2]\n\n# Mixed signs → saddle point\nif np.any(eigenvalues_saddle > 0) and np.any(eigenvalues_saddle < 0):\n    print(\"Point is a SADDLE\")"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Common mistakes — Pitfalls to avoid"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Mistake"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Correction"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Confusing Jacobian with gradient"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Jacobian = matrix (m×n); Gradient = vector (n×1)"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Not checking Hessian symmetry"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian should be symmetric: Hᵢⱼ = Hⱼᵢ"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Inverting ill-conditioned Hessian"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hessian may be nearly singular; use regularization"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Computing full Hessian"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For million parameters, Hessian is too large; use approximations"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Manual computation"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use autograd (PyTorch/TensorFlow) for Hessians"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Key takeaways"}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Gradient"},{"type":"text","text":": Vector of 1st partials for scalar output: ∇f = [∂f/∂x₁,..., ∂f/∂xₙ]"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Jacobian"},{"type":"text","text":": Matrix of ALL 1st partials for vector output: Jᵢⱼ = ∂gᵢ/∂xⱼ (m×n)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Hessian"},{"type":"text","text":": Matrix of ALL 2nd partials for scalar output: Hᵢⱼ = ∂²f/∂xᵢ∂xⱼ (n×n)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Jacobian generalizes gradient"},{"type":"text","text":": For m=1 output, Jacobian = gradient transpose"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Hessian = curvature"},{"type":"text","text":": Tells if landscape is steep/flat, convex/concave"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Hessian symmetric"},{"type":"text","text":": Hᵢⱼ = Hⱼᵢ (mixed partials equal)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Eigenvalues classify points"},{"type":"text","text":": All positive → minimum; mixed → saddle"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Newton's method"},{"type":"text","text":": Uses H⁻¹∇L for faster convergence"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sensitivity analysis"},{"type":"text","text":": Jacobian shows how outputs respond to inputs"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Rarely used"},{"type":"text","text":": Most ML uses gradients only; Hessians are expensive"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For Generative AI, Jacobians enable multi-output sensitivity analysis and backpropagation through vector-valued layers, while Hessians (though rarely computed fully) provide theoretical insights into optimization landscapes and curvature, explaining why some problems converge slowly due to \"ravines\" in the loss surface."}]}]}}
